{"id":"2110.00143","submitter":"Shijun Liao","authors":"Shijun Liao and Shijie Qin","title":"Ultra-chaos: an insurmountable objective obstacle of reproducibility and\n  replicability","comments":"17 pages, 10 figures. Accepted for publication by Advances in Applied\n  Mathematics and Mechanics in Dec. 2021","journal-ref":"Advances in Applied Mathematics and Mechanics, Vol. 14, No. 4, pp.\n  799-815 (2022)","doi":"10.4208/aamm.OA-2021-0364","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.gen-ph","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  In this paper, a new concept, i.e. ultra-chaos, is proposed for the first\ntime. Unlike a normal-chaos, statistical properties such as the probability\ndensity functions (PDF) of an ultra-chaos are sensitive to tiny disturbances.\nWe illustrate that ultra-chaos is widely existed and thus has general\nscientific meanings. It is found that statistical non-reproducibility is an\ninherent property of an ultra-chaos so that an ultra-chaos is at a higher-level\nof disorder than a normal-chaos. Thus, it is impossible in practice to\nreplicate experimental/numerical results of an ultra-chaos even in statistical\nmeanings, since random environmental noises always exist and are out of\ncontrol. Thus, the ultra-chaos should be an insurmountable obstacle of\nreproducibility and replicability. Similar to G\\\"{o}del's incompleteness\ntheorem, such kind of \"incompleteness of reproducibility\" reveals a limitation\nof our traditional scientific paradigm based on reproducible experiments, which\ncan be traced back to Galileo. The ultra-chaos opens a new door and possibility\nto study chaos theory, turbulence theory, computational fluid dynamics (CFD),\nthe statistical significance, reproducibility crisis, and so on.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 1 Oct 2021 00:41:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 20 Dec 2021 00:36:13 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-03-22"}
